<div class="section" id="html-use-elements-responsibly">
  <div class="col">
    <h3>Use Elements Responsibly</h3>
    <p>Before diving into building a site with HTML5, ensure you understand what each new element is intended for and where it belongs in your layout. These are the primary elements introduced in HTML5 that should be used, almost exclusively, when building a layout:</p>
    <h4>&lt;header&gt;</h4>
    <p>Not to be confused with &lt;head&gt;, this element designates the header, or top part, of an element or layout and can be used independently or within other elements.</p>
    <h4>&lt;hgroup&gt;</h4>
    <p>Used inside the &lt;header&gt;, the &lt;hgroup&gt; designates a grouping of header tags to help preserve typographical hierarchy and allow the browser to prioritize them as a group rather than individually. For example, you may have an H2 element as a page heading, then use another H2 for post titles, followed by an H3 for the author. The second H2 and H3 should be wrapped in an &lt;hgroup&gt; within a &lt;header&gt;.</p>
    <h4>&lt;nav&gt;</h4>
    <p>This element indicates a navigation menu, and should encapsulate an unordered list in most cases. The &lt;nav&gt; element can be used independently or within other elements, such as &lt;aside&gt;. A group of links grouped together in your content isn&rsquo;t enough reason to use the nav element. Site-wide navigation, or sub-navigation does belong in a nav element.</p>
    <h4>&lt;section&gt;</h4>
    <p>Used for grouping together thematically-related content. Sounds like a div element, but its not. The div has no semantic meaning. Before replacing all your div&rsquo;s with section elements, always ask yourself, &ldquo;Is all of the content related?&rdquo;</p>
    <h4>&lt;article&gt;</h4>
    <p>This tag represents an independent piece of content , such as a blog post or news article. It is almost always placed inside a &lt;section&gt;, but it isn&#8217;t required..</p>
    <h4>&lt;aside&gt;</h4>
    <p>The &lt;aside&gt; is most easily compared to a sidebar or any area containing content that is not directly related to the &lt;article&gt; or primary content displayed on the page. How your site is structured will depend on how you use the &lt;aside&gt;, but common practice either uses it to contain an unordered list of secondary elements, or places it inside a &lt;section&gt;, using the &lt;aside&gt; to contain each &quot;block&quot; of content. However,just because some content appears to the left or right of the main content isn&rsquo;t enough reason to use the &lt;aside&gt; element. Ask yourself if the content within the aside can be removed without reducing the meaning of the main content.</p>
    <h4>&lt;footer&gt;</h4>
    <p>Like the header, the <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code> is used to designate the foot or bottom part of an element or layout. It can be used independently, as seen in most web layouts for copyright information, or within other elements to designate &quot;footer&quot; content such as author, date, category and so on.</p>
    <h4>&lt;figure&gt;<span> &amp; <span>&lt;figcaption&gt;</h4>
    <p>Not well understood and under-used, <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code> essentially replaces the need for a <code>&lt;div class=&quot;caption&quot;&gt;</code> element used to wrap a video or image in a padded, styled box containing a description. Example:</p>
